{"title_page": "Vance Thompson", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name       = Vance Thompson\n| image      = VanceThompson.jpg\n|birth_date  = April 17, 1863\n|birth_place = \n|death_date  =  June 5, 1925\n|death_place = \n| occupation = [[Literary criticism|Literary critic]], writer}}\n\n'''Vance Thompson''' (April 17, 1863 - June 5, 1925) was an American [[Literary criticism|literary critic]], novelist, [[poet]] and [[low-carbohydrate diet]] writer. \n\n==Biography==\n\n\nThe son of a [[Pittsburgh]] pastor, he was educated at [[Princeton University]] and graduated in 1883. He later studied in Germany, and worked as a dramatic critic in [[New York City]] from 1890 to 1897. Like fellow-aesthete and good friend [[James Huneker]], he helped bring [[fin-de-si\u00e8cle]] French authors to the attention of the American public. He also wrote a study on the ego entitled ''the Ego Book: a Book of Selfish Ideals'' (1914). A study of French authors with ties to the [[Symbolism (arts)|Symbolist movement]] was published in 1913, entitled ''French Portraits: Being Appreciations of the Writers of Young France''. From 1895 to 1899, he co-edited the periodical ''M'lle New York'' with Huneker. Described as \"a highly idiosyncratic blend of serious analyses and presentations of European Symbolist literature and thought with buffoonery and incessant anti-philistinism\", it quickly became a manifesto for their cultural ideals.<ref>''The Symbolist Prints of Edvard Munch: the Vivian and David Campbell Collection.'' Page 26. Yale University Press, 1996.</ref>\n\n==Dieting==\n\nThompson authored several books on healthy living, such as 1914's ''Eat and Grow Thin'' and 1916's ''Drink and Be Sober''. \n\nHis diet book ''Eat and Grow Thin'' was popular, by 1931 it was in its 112th printing. It advocates a [[low-carbohydrate diet]] and contains a list of \"forbidden foods\".<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uva.x030577802&view=1up&seq=91 ''Eat and Grow Thin'']. (1916). ''The American Journal of Clinical Medicine'' 23 (6): 547.</ref><ref name=\"Elias\">Elias, Megan J. (2009). ''Food in the United States, 1890-1945''. ABC-CLIO. pp. 129-130. {{ISBN|978-0-313-35410-6}}</ref><ref>Kraig, Bruce. (2013). ''The Oxford Encyclopedia of Food and Drink in America, Volume 1''. Oxford University Press. p. 510. {{ISBN|978-0199734962}}</ref> Thompson believed that [[dairy]], [[pork]], [[ham]], [[bacon]], [[bean]]s, [[bread]], [[grain]]s, [[cereal]]s, [[flour]], [[rice]], [[potato]]es, [[sugar]], and all alcoholic drinks should be avoided.<ref>Elias, Megan J. (2017). ''Food on the Page: Cookbooks and American Culture''. University of Pennsylvania Press. pp. 67-68. {{ISBN|978-0812249170}}</ref> He recommended eating all kinds of meat (except pig), [[game (hunting)|game]], sea-food, eggs, fruit and green [[vegetable]]s.<ref>Thompson, Vance. (1914). [https://archive.org/details/eatgrowthinmahda00thomiala/page/42 ''Eat and Grow Thin'']. New York: E. P. Dutton. pp. 42-43</ref> The book was criticized for misrepresenting nutritional science.<ref name=\"Elias\"/>\n\nPhysiologist [[Graham Lusk]] commented that the advice from the book \"made so many of my friends so utterly miserable that I am sure that in the end it will counteract its own message.\"<ref>Lusk, Graham. (1917). [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.tz17se&view=1up&seq=355 ''Food In War Time'']. ''The Scientific Monthly'' 5: 307.</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n[[File:Eat and Grow Thin.png|thumb|''Eat and Grow Thin'', 1914]]\n\n*[https://archive.org/details/frenchportraits00thomiala ''French Portraits: Being Appreciations of the Writers of Young France''] (1900) \n*''Spinners of Life'' (1904)\n*''Diplomatic Mysteries'' (1905)\n*[https://archive.org/details/lifeofethelbertn000845mbp ''The Life of Ethelbert Nevin''] (1913) \n*[https://archive.org/details/egobookbookofsel00thomiala ''The Ego Book: A Book of Selfish Ideals''] (1914) \n*''The Night Watchman and Other Poems'' (1914)\n*[https://archive.org/details/eatgrowthinmahda00thomiala ''Eat and Grow Thin: The Mahdah Menus''] (1914) \n*[https://archive.org/details/drinkbesober00thom/page/n6 ''Drink and Be Sober''] (1915)\n*[https://archive.org/details/versenight00thomrich ''Verse''] (1915) \n*[https://archive.org/details/carnivalofdestin00thomiala ''The Carnival of Destiny''] (1916) \n*''The Peace Girl'' (1916)\n*[https://archive.org/details/womanandword00thomuoft ''Woman''] (1917) \n*[https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/100630573 ''Live and Be Young''] (1920)\n*''The Pointed Tower'' (1923)\n*''The Green Ray'' (1924)\n*''The Scarlet Iris'' (1924)\n*''Mr. Guelpa'' (1925)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.crcstudio.arts.ualberta.ca/americandecadence/viewtext.php?s=browse&tid=20&dt=5&route=bythisdoctype.php&start=12 Scans of ''M'lle Yew York'' at the ''American Decadence'' website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thompson, Vance}}\n\n[[Category:1863 births]]\n[[Category:1925 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American poets]]\n[[Category:American literary critics]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:Low-carbohydrate diet advocates]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscientific diet advocates]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name       = Vance Thompson\n| image      = VanceThompson.jpg\n|birth_date  = April 17, 1863\n|birth_place = \n|death_date  =  June 5, 1925\n|death_place = \n| occupation = [[Literary criticism|Literary critic]], writer}}\n\n'''Vance Thompson''' (April 17, 1863 - June 5, 1925) was an American [[Literary criticism|literary critic]], novelist, [[poet]] and [[low-carbohydrate diet]] writer. \n\n==Biography==\n\n\nThe son of a [[Pittsburgh]] pastor, he was educated at [[Princeton University]] and graduated in 1883. He later studie